ğŸ§© Problem Idea

We have to place N queens on an NÃ—N chessboard so that:

No two queens attack each other.

Queens attack along rows, columns, and diagonals.

ğŸ§± Code Explanation (Every Line)
def print_board(board):
    for row in board:
        print(" ".join(row))
    print()


Purpose: Prints the chessboard nicely.

board is a 2D list (like a matrix) made of "." (empty) and "Q" (queen).

" ".join(row) joins all elements of the row with spaces.

Example: ["Q", ".", ".", "."] â†’ "Q . . ."

def is_safe(board, row, col, n):


Checks if a queen can be safely placed at position (row, col).

ğŸ§© Step-by-step inside is_safe
    # check column
    for i in range(row):
        if board[i][col] == "Q":
            return False


Looks vertically up in the same column.

If any previous row already has a "Q" in the same column â†’ return False.

    # check left diagonal
    i, j = row - 1, col - 1
    while i >= 0 and j >= 0:
        if board[i][j] == "Q":
            return False
        i -= 1
        j -= 1


Checks the upper-left diagonal.

Moves diagonally up and left (â†–).

If it finds any "Q" â†’ not safe.

    # check right diagonal
    i, j = row - 1, col + 1
    while i >= 0 and j < n:
        if board[i][j] == "Q":
            return False
        i -= 1
        j += 1


Checks the upper-right diagonal (â†—).

Same logic: if any "Q" found â†’ not safe.

    return True


If no queen conflicts found â†’ the spot is safe.

def solve_n_queens(board, row, n):


Recursive function that tries to place queens row by row.

Base idea: Place one queen in each row safely using recursion.

Inside solve_n_queens
    if row == n:
        print_board(board)
        return


Base case: If we have reached past the last row, all queens are placed â†’ print board (solution found).

    for col in range(n):
        if is_safe(board, row, col, n):
            board[row][col] = "Q"
            solve_n_queens(board, row + 1, n)
            board[row][col] = "."


Loops through each column in current row.

If (row, col) is safe:

Place queen ("Q").

Move to next row (row+1) â†’ recursion.

When done, remove queen (".") â†’ backtracking step (try next position).

n = 4
board = [["."] * n for _ in range(n)]
board[0][1] = "Q"  # first queen placed
print("Initial Board:")
print_board(board)
print("Solutions:")
solve_n_queens(board, 1, n)


Creates a 4Ã—4 empty board.

Puts one queen manually at row 0, column 1.

Prints initial board.

Calls solver starting from row 1 (since first row is filled).

